  <para id="fs-id1406623">In both cases, there is an outside force doing work on the object (crane, push). But there is another force acting in the opposite direction (gravity, friction) that also does work, so there is no net change in kinetic energy. However, gravity is a conservative force, and the object lifted by a crane now has more potential energy than it did before. Friction is a nonconservative force, so the object pushed across the rough surface does not have any change in potential energy.</para>
  </solution>-->
